<!---->
<poetry xmlns="http://www.sibawayhi.org/schema/2024/05/igt" bab="024">
   <verses id="٤٦٧١٣" nbr="1">
      <verse>
         <hemistiche>
            <text>
               <ar>فَأَمَّا تَمِيْمٌ تَمِيْمُ بْنُ مُرٍّ</ar>
               <free>so as for Tamīm{\influn},<ed>the</ed>Tamīm{\influ} bn{\influ} murr{\inflin}</free>
            </text>
            <igt>
               <t>
                  <ar>فَأَمَّا</ar>
                  <en/>
               </t>
               <t>
                  <ar>تَمِيْمٌ</ar>
                  <en/>
               </t>
               <t>
                  <ar>تَمِيْمُ</ar>
                  <en/>
               </t>
               <t>
                  <ar>بِنُ</ar>
                  <en/>
               </t>
               <t>
                  <ar>مُرٍّ</ar>
                  <en/>
               </t>
            </igt>
         </hemistiche>
         <hemistiche>
            <text>
               <ar>فَأَلْفَاْهُمُ الْقَوْمُ رَوْبَى نِيَاْمَا</ar>
               <free>well the people found them disordered, drowsy</free>
            </text>
            <igt>
               <t>
                  <ar>فَأَلْفَاْهُمُ</ar>
                  <en/>
               </t>
               <t>
                  <ar>الْقَوْمُ</ar>
                  <en/>
               </t>
               <t>
                  <ar>رَوْبَى</ar>
                  <en/>
               </t>
               <t>
                  <ar>نِيَاْمَا</ar>
                  <en/>
               </t>
            </igt>
         </hemistiche>
      </verse>
   </verses>
   <verses id="٩٨٧٢٩" nbr="2">
      <verse>
         <hemistiche>
            <text>
               <ar>إِذَا ابْنُ أَبِي مُوْسَى بِلَاْلٌ بَلَغْتِهِ</ar>
               <free>if, the son{\influ}<ed>of</ed>abī mūsa, Bilāl{\influn}, you deliver me to him,</free>
            </text>
            <igt>
               <t>
                  <ar>إِذَا</ar>
                  <en/>
               </t>
               <t>
                  <ar>ابْنُ</ar>
                  <en/>
               </t>
               <t>
                  <ar>أَبِي</ar>
                  <en/>
               </t>
               <t>
                  <ar>مُوْسَى</ar>
                  <en/>
               </t>
               <t>
                  <ar>بِلَاْلٌ</ar>
                  <en/>
               </t>
               <t>
                  <ar>بَلَغْتِهِ</ar>
                  <en/>
               </t>
            </igt>
         </hemistiche>
         <hemistiche>
            <text>
               <ar>فَقَاْمَ بِفَأْسٍ بَيْنَ وُصْلَيْكِ جَاْزِرُ</ar>
               <free>then let him rise, with an axe, between your two joints, slaughtering</free>
            </text>
            <igt>
               <t>
                  <ar>فَقَاْمَ</ar>
                  <en/>
               </t>
               <t>
                  <ar>بِفَأْسٍ</ar>
                  <en/>
               </t>
               <t>
                  <ar>بَيْنَ</ar>
                  <en/>
               </t>
               <t>
                  <ar>وُصْلَيْكِ</ar>
                  <en/>
               </t>
               <t>
                  <ar>جَاْزِرُ</ar>
                  <en/>
               </t>
            </igt>
         </hemistiche>
      </verse>
      <comment>
        The poet addresses his <xar>نَاْقَة</xar> (female camel): if you bring me to him (who is known for his
        generosity) I'll no longer need you so I'll have someone slaughter you.
      </comment>
   </verses>
</poetry>
